Dear Viking Families,

It is the end of July and, as promised, we are sharing our 1st draft of the Whitehall return to school plan. This plan will be updated weekly. We are committed to working with you to resolve issues and provide clearer communication.

Additional details will be added to this plan as we learn more and are provided with more clarification from the health department and the Governor's office. The plan is designed to follow the strongly recommended and required components of the Return to School Road Map (link included in document) provided by the Governor.

If you have any questions or concerns, please feel free to contact me at jerrymcdowell@whitehallschools.net or by phone at 231.893.1001. It will be challenging to address any questions via Facebook.

Thanks in advance for your understanding and patience during this pandemic. Our goal is to provide a safe, caring, thoughtful learning environment for your children.

https://www.whitehallschools.net/downloads/districtfiles/whitehall_return_to_school_plan_-_draft_rvd._7.26.20.pdf

Whitehall Food Service will continue to distribute meals on a weekly basis at Whitehall High School and Whitehall Middle School on Tuesday from 10am-12pm until August 18th.

Huge shout out to our food service staff who have distributed over 220,000 meals since the start of the shut down on March 16th. They have endured freezing temperatures, sweltering heat and pouring rain, all the time cheerfully doing their job of taking care of children.

Many thanks to the team!

We are excited to announce that 4th grade teachers, Britney Christensen and Gabe Knowles, from Ealy Elementary will work with Dr. Doug Landis to roll out the reGrow Milkweed for Monarchs: Citizen Science Project this summer. https://www.canr.msu.edu/msumilkweedregrow/

Research experiences for teachers are authentic research experiences that pair a classroom teacher with a scientist. We are so delighted that the National Science Foundation, as part of the KBS Long-term Ecological Research (LTER) Program, has funded this two year project, “Harnessing disturbance to enhance monarch butterfly conservation”.

post_text:
The GreenScreens film festival winners were announced at our "virtual screening" last Thursday. Starting in September, all 8th grade students chose an environmental topic that they were passionate about and worked all year long, including during the shutdown to complete their documentaries. These film documentaries are truly interdisciplinary projects using Science as a base, but writing film scripts in English, graphs in math and researching history. Students even experienced multimedia work by gathering pictures and video, doing voice-overs, adding music and sound effects and even film editing.

1st, 2nd, and 3rd place prizes were awarded from the ten finalists thanks to a grant from the West Michigan Great Lakes Stewardship Initiative. If you didn't get a chance to see the video tribute, enjoy the show here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=riMYxlxG3XE&feature=youtu.be

Beginning Friday, 5/8/20 - Whitehall Schools is providing internet access for students' use for school work in three areas of our district.

The password for all hotspots is: GoVikes1

Blue Lake Residences Office - parents may park in front of office or along side of road near office (face the building, as hotspot is in east front window)

Lakewood Club Village Hall - may park in grass, east of storage shed between parking lot & dirt road (face south for best reception)

Duck Lake Learning Center - may park as close to the north-west corner of the building as possible (in/on handicap parking spot is best...face the building for best reception)

post_text:
Dale McKenzie, long time Viking educator and leader, announced his plans to retire earlier this school year. He is a true Viking in every way. Over the last few months we have conducted a search to replace this dedicated educator!

The position of High School Principal has been offered to Brett Westerlund. Brett immediately accepted and is ready to become our new high school leader.

Brett is a Whitehall community member. He is married to Ashley (also an educator) and they have two children who attend Whitehall Schools. Brett taught at Fruitport High School and is currently the Assistant Principal at Fremont High School.

If you know Brett, please welcome him aboard. And if you do not, please look for him around the district. Go Vikings!

Like all of you, we can't wait to get back to school. But until we do ... please stay safe, wash your hands, and be the best Viking that you can be!

post_text:
Hi Vikings,

Most of us love a routine. One of the hard things about all of this corona closure is the major disruption in our lives. There just wasn't a whole lot of time to prepare for it ... and there really isn't a playbook on how to handle it. None of us (parents, teachers, children) had a lot of time to plan for being out of school so suddenly. It really has been jarring.

We share this note because it is important to recognize that our kids loved their routine just as much as we do. Keep an eye on all of OUR children and try and share a sense of where we are all coming from as we work to develop a new routine.

We wish we were in school too!

post_text:
This calming brain break is wonderful in moments where the
teacher (parent) and students (children) need to reset and when the class (family) is approaching dysregulation.

1. Take a deep breath in for a count of two.
2. Breathe out for a count of two.
3. Repeat in counts of 4, 6, and 8.

For real, thanks for all that you are doing at home. We miss you already as much as you miss us!

In case you were wondering:

The Michigan High School Athletic Association has directed all member schools to suspend activities in all sports for all seasons– effective Monday, March 16 through at least Sunday, April 5 – to fall in line with Gov. Gretchen Whitmer’s order that all schools close for the next three weeks in order to deter the spread of COVID-19.

All athletic activities to be halted include practices, scrimmages and competitions/games, as well as strength training, conditioning and any other organized sessions and activities in all MHSAA in-season and out-of-season sports.

The coronavirus has caused some very complex decisions to have to be made. Every decision impacts people in different ways. There are many questions regarding the details of these decision to close schools. We will work to provide answers to these questions as we gain more information.

We will communicate in three ways ... Coronavirus updates will will be posted on our website. We will send school messages through our Intouch email system, our Intouch text system, and Facebook.

I can be reached at jerrymcdowell@whitehallschools.net or directly at 231.893.1001. While I may not be able to answer you immediately I will work to respond as soon as I am able.

Thanks in advance for your patience and assistance to keep our students and community safe.

post_text: Staff at Whitehall Middle School are cutting back on their disposable paper product usage thanks to the school's Lexus Eco Challenge team, Climate Justice Warriors. The team replaced paper napkins with reusable linen napkins (sewn by the team) for the staff lounge, which will save almost 5,000 napkins per year. Napkins will be hung-up and reused all week--teachers select a labeled clothespin to mark their napkin. At the end of each week, napkins will be washed by students in Mrs. Feenstra's class. The team also created Eco Party Packs with reusable plates, bowls, cups, and silverware for staff potlucks, and class/team parties. This will cut down on high usage of single-use paper and plastic products. The Climate Justice Warriors want to encourage all students and the community to reduce their use and save the trees!

post_text: Emergency personnel have responded to a crash involving a small plane near the Whitehall Athletic Fields at Sophia St. This accident was on city property and DID NOT involve any students or staff. There was a loud boom and smoke that was visible to some students (particularly the 7th grade) from the school. This will warrant a discussion with your children this evening. We are all safe and our schools will continue to operate a normal schedule.
